<br>
Solve the problem. Don't delay it, don't appease it temporarily. Make a plan that is realistic that will solve your problem permanantly, then execute that plan.<br>
<br>
I don't think being drunk while at work will solve your problems. It might feel like they're farther away for a little while but it won't stop them from being there the next day.<br>
<br>
You're a parent. Do you really want your child growing in the shadow of someone who's solution is alcohol? Even if you're raising one hell of a little monster, the kid deserves a mother who's going to try a little bit harder than getting &quot;toasty&quot; at work, don't you think?<br>
<br>
When your kid's older and the kid starts making your life hell, are you just going to get &quot;toasty&quot; at home so that you don't recognize you have problems?<br>
<br>
If you're strong enough to still be alive and a single mom, then you're strong enough to get past this work problem too. Just buckle down, get a plan, and start busting your ass to improve your life and the life your little brat has too.<br>
<br>
Last suggestion for you: if you have someone you can talk to, who's life isn't in shambles, maybe they can give better advice than random people on the message board for a video game? Maybe there's some sort of family planning clinic or government advisement office you can visit and get some ideas if all you can come up with is booze, I dunno, not a situation I'll ever wind up in. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bouncerlunarx>Bouncer LunarX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 167<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/3/03 2:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1916.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: rofl</span><hr size=1> All of Saalron's points are valid and realistic. Don't delay things, find a permanent way to fix it. Go to one of those clinics he mentioned or a psychologist/psychiatrist or something and they can guide you step by step to fix the problems. Also need a strong will and determination to fix it, if you don't have it, your going to be stuck there and it'll never go away. <p>Evilgohanz Nightfire, Arch Lich of Triality</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kandrak>Kandrak</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 171<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(2/3/03 2:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1916.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Drinking on the Job</span><hr size=1> There are always possibilities, you never really k